class Solution {
    public int maximalSquare(char[][] matrix) {
        int max = 0;
        int [][] dp = new int[matrix.length][matrix[0].length];
        for (int i = 0; i < matrix.length; i++){
            if (matrix[i][0] == '1'){
                dp[i][0] = 1;
                max = 1;
            } else{
                dp[i][0] = 0;
            }
        }
        for (int j = 0; j < matrix[0].length; j++){
            if (matrix[0][j] == '1'){
                dp[0][j] = 1;
                max = 1;
            } else{
                dp[0][j] = 0;
            }
        }
        for (int i = 1; i < matrix.length; i++){
            for (int j = 1; j < matrix[0].length; j++){
                if (matrix[i][j] != '0'){
                    dp[i][j] = 1 + Math.min(dp[i - 1][j], Math.min(dp[i][j - 1], dp[i - 1][j - 1]));
                } else{
                    dp[i][j] = 0;
                }
                max = Math.max(max, dp[i][j]);
            }
        }
        return max * max;
    }
}

/*
Notes:

(Using “Dynamic Programming”.)

Value functions of Q221: dp(i,j) = min( dp(i−1,j), dp(i−1,j−1), dp(i,j−1) ) + 1

Explanation: 
  If current value equals to 0, the there is not any square exist, we set its dp to 0. 
  If current value equals to 1: The largest square of current position equals to 1 add the minimum of its left one, upper one and left-top one.

*”Boundary condition”: 
  1. We set the dp value of leftmost column to 1 if its original value is ‘1’ or to 0 if its original value is ‘0’.
  2. We set the dp value of top row to 1 if its original value is ‘1’ or to 0 if its original value is ‘0’.
  3. We start from dp[1][1] instead of dp[0][0]

*/
